{{Infobox person |name = Aggie Grey |image = |imagesize = |caption = |birth_name = |birth_date = |birth_place = [[Western Samoa]] |occupation = Hotellier |years_active = }}
'''Aggie Grey''' was born in [[Western Samoa]] in 1897 and died in 1988. She was a well-known hotelier and founder of [[Grey Investment Group]] and [[Aggie Grey's Hotel and Bungalows|Aggie Grey's Hotel]].<ref name="Hotel in Apia Upolu">http://www.pacificislandtravel.com [http://www.pacificislandtravel.com/samoa/hotels/aggiegreyhotelapia.asp Hotel in Apia (Upolu)]</ref>
==Biography== Aggie Grey was born Agnes Genevieve Swann,<ref name="AGGIE GREY'S">travellinglady.tweedies.biz [http://travellinglady.tweedies.biz/country/wsamoa/aggies.htm "AGGIE GREY'S"] The hotel that became a legend in the South Pacific</ref> the daughter of William Swann an English chemist and his Samoan wife Pele.<ref name="Hotel in Apia Upolu"/> In 1903 her mother died and she was raised by her father and later by him and her step mother. Aggie Grey is the subject of two biographies by Nelson Eustis<ref name=":0">{{cite book |title=Aggie Grey |last=Eustis |first=Nelson |publisher=Hobby Editions |year=1979 |isbn=978-0-9595609-0-9 |location=United States |pages=}}</ref> and Fay Alailima,<ref>{{cite book |title=Aggie Grey: A Samoan Saga |last=Alailima |first=Fay |publisher=Mutual, USA |year=1988 |isbn=978-0-935180-79-4 |location=United States |pages=}}</ref> was on several postage stamps of Western Samoa,<ref>{{cite book |title=Stanley Gibbons Commonwealth Stamp Catalogue: Eastern Pacific, |last=Stanley Gibbons Limited (2007). |first= |publisher= |year=2007 |edition=1st |isbn=978-0-85259-644-9 |location=London and Ringwood: Stanley Gibbons Limited. |pages=50}}</ref> and was a pioneering figure of the Samoan hotel industry.<ref name=":1">{{cite news |url=http://www.samoaobserver.ws/home/headlines/6407-aggies-signs-up-to-global-hotel-group |title=Samoan Observer |last= |first= |date=8 August 2013 |work="Aggie's signs up to Global Hotel Group" |access-date=10 September 2015 |via=http://www.samoaobserver.ws/home/headlines/6407-aggies-signs-up-to-global-hotel-group|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130812030809/http://www.samoaobserver.ws/home/headlines/6407-aggies-signs-up-to-global-hotel-group|archivedate=12 August 2013}}</ref> Aggie Grey died in 1988.<ref name="books.google.com.au"/>
In her adult life she became popular on the Samoan social scene.<ref name="books.google.com.au">The Samoans: A Global Family By Frederic Koehler Sutter [https://books.google.com/books?id=AtUCyMG-hqIC&pg=PA161&lpg=PA161&dq=Aggie+Grey+Olaf&source=bl&hl=en Page 14 Aggie Grey: West Point Hotelier, Legend. Apia, Upolu, Samoa]</ref> She founded her hotel in 1933,<ref name="Hotel in Apia Upolu"/> and became one of Samoa's most popular and well known figures.<ref name="AGGIE GREY'S"/> She hosted many notable actors, including [[Dorothy Lamour]], [[Marlon Brando]], [[Gary Cooper]], [[William Holden]], [[Raymond Burr]] and [[Robert Morley]] who stayed at her hotel. Her hotel was involved with the production and housing of the crew on the American film production of [[Return to Paradise (1953 film)|Return to Paradise]] (1953) starring Gary Cooper.
She was friends with American writer [[James A. Michener|James Michener]] and she and her sister Mary Croudace (Aunty Mary) were widely believed to be possible models for his character [[Bloody Mary (South Pacific)|Bloody Mary]] that he created in ''[[Tales of the South Pacific]]'' (1946). The book was adapted into Broadway's [[musical theatre|musical]] blockbuster ''[[South Pacific (musical)|South Pacific]]'' (1949) by [[Richard Rodgers|Rodgers]] and [[Oscar Hammerstein II|Hammerstein]] (collectively known as [[Rodgers and Hammerstein]]), and subsequently the 1958 film [[South Pacific (1958 film)|South Pacific]].
Aggie Gray's sister Mary Croudace ran "The Casino" a boarding-house in Apia, and was reputed to have been the lover of a Marine general in the war. Mr Croudace, reputed to have been a New Zealand official, was long gone.<ref>{{cite book |last= [[Gerald Hensley|Hensley]] |first= Gerald |title= Final Approaches: A Memoir |accessdate= |edition= |origyear= |year= 2006 |publisher= Auckland University Press, NZ |location= Auckland |isbn= 1 86940 378 9 |oclc= |page= 6 |pages= }}</ref><ref name=":2">{{cite journal|first= Kirsten Moana |last=Thompson |title=The Construction of a Myth: Bloody Mary, Aggie Grey and the Optics of Tourism |journal=Journal of New Zealand and Pacific Studies |volume=2 |number=1 |date=April 2014 |pages= 5–19|url = http://www.ingentaconnect.com/content/intellect/nzps/2014/00000002/00000001/art00002|accessdate = 2015-09-09|authorlink = Kirsten Moana Thompson}}</ref>
The Aggie Grey Hotel is now three resorts, two on Upolu island in Samoa, in Apia and Aggie's Lagoon and one resort, Le Méredien in Tahiti.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://aggiegreys.com |title=Aggie Grey's Company |date= |accessdate=10 September 2015 |website=Aggie Greys.com |publisher= |last= |first= }}</ref> In 2013 Aggie Grey's became part of the Sheraton chain.<ref name=":1" />
==References== {{Reflist}} * {{cite journal |title=The construction of a myth: Bloody Mary, Aggie Grey and the optics of tourism |url=http://www.ingentaconnect.com/content/intellect/nzps/2014/00000002/00000001/art00002 |journal=Journal of New Zealand & Pacific Studies |date=2014-04-01 |pages=5–19 |volume=2 |issue=1 |doi=10.1386/nzps.2.1.5_1 |first=Kirsten Moana |last=Thompson}}
